A West Garden
You are standing in a resplendent graden. The carefully curated flower beds are marvelous to behold. Just a few of the flowers you can see include chrysanthemums, red orchids, pointesettias, roses, poppies, hybiscuses, petunias, and many more. The garden is ringed by tall green hedges, with an exit to the NorthEast. In the middle of the graden stands a simple yet elegant statue. The statue depicts a father standing lovingly beside his son. The father is wearing a battered iron helmet that reads "Alexios Angelos II". The son has a vacant look on his face and the father appears to be searching wistfully. Tightly clenched in the fathers other hand is a brilliant red ruby.
> give helmet to statue

> give helmet to statue
The statue of the father gratefully accepts the helmet and places it tenderly on his sons head. His son's vacant look disappears and is replaced with an expression of pure gratitude and joy. The father smiles at you and hands you his ruby.
> northeast

> northeast

A North Garden
You are standing in a resplendent graden. The carefully curated flower beds are marvelous to behold. Just a few of the flowers you can see include periwinkles, hydrangeas, forget-me-not's, columbines, lupines, himalayan blue poppies, and many more. The garden is ringed by tall green hedges, with exits to the SouthEast, SouthWest. There is also an enormous steel door to the North with three pedestals arrayed in front of it. The first pedestal glows a vibrant red, the second pedestal glows a vibrant blue, and the third pedestal glows a vibrant yellow. In the middle of the graden a small plum tree laden down with a bountiful harvest grows.
As you marvel at the magnificent garden, an old and wizened hag steps forth from the shadows. She is clothed in many layers of foul cloth and leather. Her wizened face is shrunken deep into the cavernous folds of her clothing and she gimly clutches a gnarled staff. Atop the staff sits a beautiful blue saphire.
"If you can bring me what I ask of I just may let you borrow my jewel." the hag croaks. "Bring me what the small folk eat, and the big folk's mouths. Simply place them in my cauldron here, deary."
With a wave of her hand the hag creates a black iron cauldron and shuffles off into the shadows.
